<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple CSS Example</title>

    <style>
        /* Styling the body */
        body {
            background-color: #f0f8ff;
            /* Light blue background */
            color: #333;
            /* Dark grey text color */
            font-size: 18px;
            /* Font size set to 18px */
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            /* Use Arial or sans-serif */
        }

        /* Styling the heading */
        h1 {
            color: #00509e;
            /* Blue color for heading text */
        }

        /* Styling the paragraph */
        p {
            color: #444;
            /* Slightly lighter grey for paragraph text */
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>
    <h1>Welcome to My Webpage</h1>
    <p>This is a basic example of HTML with embedded CSS styling.</p>
</body>

</html>

<!-- Summary and Explanation
1. Single File Structure:
We use the <style> tag inside the <head> section to define the CSS. This is known as embedded CSS.
The HTML structure remains in the <body> section with the heading (<h1>) and a paragraph (<p>).
2. How the CSS Works:
body: Sets the background color to light blue (#f0f8ff), text color to dark grey (#333), font size to 18px, and the font family to Arial or sans-serif.
h1: Changes the heading text color to blue (#00509e).
p: Sets the paragraph text color to a lighter grey (#444).
3. Result in Browser:
When this file is opened, the page will display:
A light blue background.
The heading text will be blue, and the paragraph text will appear in light grey.
Both the heading and paragraph text will use Arial or a fallback sans-serif font.
This approach simplifies the setup since all styles and content are in one file. However, for larger projects, separating CSS into external files helps with organization and reuse. -->